				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12496767/scp-4773-2#post-4358448</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 10 Sep 2019 19:11:30 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>ADream</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>5112585</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>This seems really similar to SCP-4031, both being about a guy who makes people unable to perceive him and then gets accidentally killed by the Foundation. However, reading that last collapsible caused such a powerful reaction in me that I feel the execution is strong enough to stand on its own. The fact that the article doesn't overstay its welcome definitely helps in that sense.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12496767#post-4358325</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12496767/scp-4773-2#post-4358325</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 10 Sep 2019 16:26:46 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Gentleman Thief</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1782925</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>This fell a bit flat for me. The article does pretty much the same thing as <a href="http://www.scpwiki.com/scp-3942">3942</a>, but the mystery unfolds in a much faster and, in my opinion, less satisfying way.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12496767#post-4358218</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12496767/scp-4773-2#post-4358218</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 10 Sep 2019 14:26:28 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>T Rutherford</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4620432</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>See, Malice, this is why people keep saying you're an underappreciated author. This is an excellent article. It's subtle, clever, and the twist is utterly gut-wrenching.</p> <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">A&nbsp;quick&nbsp;crit</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">A&nbsp;quick&nbsp;crit</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <p>I do agree with some of the comments here, though. The narrative falls a bit flat when you ask why the foundation didn't realize the the -1 was a living kid. Also, if it could freely manipulate objects that were fully perceptible, how it didn't try to communicate more. Still, those are very minor plot-holes allowing the story to be told.</p> <p>The visual elements are brilliant, but beyond that, you do tend to dawdle a bit in the description phase. The footnotes and crossed-out sections peeking through the memetic effects are nice, but they go overboard in sections. I've never been a fan of ongoing revision style storytelling in articles though, so I'm biased.</p> <p>The best part is by far the ending. It's so brief and cold-cut, just raw facts. Very chilling.</p> </div> </div> </div> <p>Overall, +1 for sure.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
